2020A_C003.specialRequests: We request that the schedule of nights for the Doppler planets searches of the California Planet  Search (CPS) be determined with two goals in mind. First, we request that 1/2 of our nights be  bunched into high-cadence campaigns (defined below). Second, we request that the other 1/2 of  the nights be spread evenly through the remaining time, with at least one CPS night per  lunation. We prefer first half nights for the setting TESS targets. We request (if possible) the  scheduling of 1-2 high-cadence campaigns for CPS as a whole. We define high-cadence  campaign as ~8 nights allocated in ~16 calendar nights. This allocation of nights will maximize  the scientific yield of this proposal and other projects within CPS, while focusing our primary  observing time on targets that are yet to be identified by the TESS satellite. We have targets  available at all RA, ten of which are listed below (most are notional targets).    Our proposed distribution of nights will allow us to track planets with orbital periods of days to  weeks (a large part of our sample) as well as months and longer (also important). Our programs  can easily accommodate half or fractional nights; they are especially advantageous during the  high cadence period to increase coverage. Expected PIs for this project (the TESS-Keck  Survey) in 2020A will be Howard (NASA), Howard (Caltech), and Petigura (UC). PIs from the  broader CPS collaboration include Howard, Petigura, Fulton, Kane, Batalha, Dressing, Weiss,  Huber, Crossfield, and Robertson. In the past we have been awarded ~30-50 nights/semester in  total. We recognize that scheduling is difficult (perhaps over constrained) and thank the Keck  staff for their efforts. The PI is happy to consult by email/phone to facilitate scheduling.

2020A_C197.specialRequests: In this proposal we ask for five half nights to observe a subset of the 12 exoplanet systems in our Direct Detection program. We are testing an observing strategy that prioritizes epochs where the primary velocity of the system is small. Therefore, we prefer half nights that have multiple targets up and with near-zero primary velocities. There are a few specific half nights that we could not accept however, because the systems up during those half nights are in near conjuncture positions so that planetary lines would not be well separated from the stellar lines. These specific half nights that we could not accept are: (1st half night) 2/2, 2/3, 2/5, 2/9, 2/11, 2/14, 2/16, 2/21, 2/23, 2/28, 3/03, 3/06, 4/26, 5/28, 5/31, 6/2, 6/4, 6/6, 6/10, 6/12, 6/14, 6/17, 6/25, 7/4, 7/5, 7/10, 7/13, 7/14, 7/15, 7/18, 7/20, 7/21, 7/23, 7/24, 7/25, 7/29, and (2nd half night) 2/28, 3/01, 3/03, 3/09, 3/11, 3/22, 3/24, 3/26, 3/28, 4/13, 4/16, 4/18, 4/23, 4/24, 4/25, 4/26, 5/3, 5/4, 5/6, 5/14, 5/15, 5/16, 5/17, 5/20, 5/24, 5/25, 5/26, 5/31, 6/3, 6/4, 6/6, 6/14, 6/17, 6/23, 6/25, 7/14, 7/25. Any other half night would be acceptable. We recognize that NIRSPEC is due to be unavailable from February into mid-March, but we list sub-optimal nights here too in case the instrument is ready earlier than expected.    If full nights are allocated instead, the time requested for the WD/BD binaries (proposal C199) could be folded in. If scheduled, we will share our quantitative assessment of the performance of NIRSPEC2.0 with the Keck community in as timely a fashion as possible.

It is not imperative that the L and M nights be adjacent. It would be helpful, but not imperative, for the two M band half nights to be back-to-back. If it would be more helpful to the scheduler to make the two M-band have night and one L-band half night requests separately in the table below, we can update this cover sheet.
